{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "St. Albert the Great defines the Eucharist as 'spiritual food,' by stating that 'the ultimate effect of this Sacrament is the grace of spiritually eating and drinking.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "According to him, the Body of Christ is truly present in the sacramental species; he thinks that the Body of Christ is also present in the stomach of the disciple when he receives the Eucharist, and even in the stomach of someone who receives it unworthily; indeed, in general, the Body of Christ in its integrity is present wherever one can see the consecrated species of bread and wine.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "By transubstantiation, the bread and wine are entirely changed and instead the Body and Blood of Christ become present, so that nothing of the bread and wine remains after the consecration of the Mass.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Commenting on the famous words from the Gospel of John in which Jesus says that His Flesh is true food and His Blood is true drink (Jn 6:55), Albert says that the type of nourishment provided by this food is spiritual and its aim is that we remain in Christ, since he, by his union with the divinity, is the source of perpetual life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The 'truth' of this food proceeds from the first cause that makes it food.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "To be food is to contribute to life in a vegetative way.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "However, in the case of the Eucharist, this food contributes to the truest life possible for a man, the life of grace and glory.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Since this is the highest life, in this food the notion of 'food' is used in the most perfect mode.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The nature of nourishment of the Eucharist should not be explained as a kind of metaphor.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "This food satisfies men to the point that everybody who takes it does not desire any other sustenance, although he has to take additional nourishment to support the body.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The sustenance provided by the Eucharist suppresses the desires for honor, pleasure, wealth, etc.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Therefore, it eliminates every sort of hunger, unless the disciple voluntarily abandons the communion with Christ.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Despite being a 'true food,' the Eucharist differs from other common foods because they nourish living beings in order to preserve their temporal and mortal life, while this Sacrament provides immortal life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "When there is a defect in conventional feeding processes, it can be attributed either to the nutrient, or to the living being that is being fed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "In the case of the Eucharist, the food may not be beneficial for the communicant because of the lack of his preparation or readiness, but certainly there cannot be any defect in the nutrient as such, because it always contains the power to lead the recipient to eternal life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "According to Albert, conventional food acquires the power to nourish from vegetative soul itself, which has to exercise a transformation in it in order to make it nutritious in act; the soul makes it 'similar' to the living being that is being fed: therefore, nutrition is 'assimilation.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "But this means that the nutrient cannot overcome the nature of the living being that it will nourish: if the living being is corruptible, its food becomes part of a corruptible body and, sooner or later, it will eventually be corrupted.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Nevertheless, just the opposite takes place, namely, that the Body of Christ transmutes Christians into Him, so that their weakness is overcome and they gain strength and even eternal life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Finally, Christ behaves as a good shepherd who admirably grazes his flock and gives it to eat his own Body and thus transforms it into his Body; so, by evoking the wedding hymn sung by Adam, He makes Christians flesh of His flesh and bone of His bones.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "The third aspect in which the Eucharist differs from ordinary food is its character of general nourishment of both soul and body.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
